<DIV3 N="7" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>VII.</HEAD>
<P><HI>MAELOC CRWM,</HI> of <HI>Llechwedd-i&s;af,</HI> and <HI>Creuddyn</HI> <NOTE N="&dagger;" PLACE="foot">Both the&s;e places are in <HI>Caernarvon&s;hire.</HI></NOTE>, lived in the time of Prince <HI>David ap Owain Gwynedd,</HI> about the year of our Lord 1175, (as Sir <HI>Thomas ap Williams'</HI> book averreth). What offices he bore, I have not learned. The mo&s;t famous men de&s;cended of him were, Sir <HI>Thomas Chaloner,</HI> and others of that name, de&s;cended of <HI>David Chaloner,</HI> of <HI>Denbigh,</HI> who&s;e ance&s;tor <HI>Trahaiarn Chaloner</HI> was &s;o called, becau&s;e his grand|father <HI>Madoc Crwm</HI> of <HI>Chaloner</HI> had lived in a town in <HI>France</HI> called <HI>Chaloner,</HI> whence he took that name.&mdash;<HI>He beareth argent, on a cheveron &s;able, three angels or.</HI></P>
